Files ending &#39;.warc.gz&#39; may be decompressed with anything that handles 
&#39;gzip&#39; (.gz) files.

If working with a lot of bulk streamed files on Windows, it may be 
useful to familiarize yourself with the &#39;cygwin&#39; package of 
Unix-utilities-on-Windows.

On Unixes (and cygwin), the usual command for decompressing gzip data is 
&#39;gzip&#39; (with proper options), which is usually aliased to &#39;gunzip&#39; or 
&#39;zcat&#39; (for handy decompression).

Note that all such decompression will give you the raw WARC records, 
which include lots of crawl metadata and HTTP headers, rather than just 
individual files of different URL contents.

